I fixed a two-year memory leak. Deployed. Memory dropped 70%.

Then the 499s came back.

Turns out there were TWO leaks hiding in the same codebase. The first was HTTP disposal (missing `using` statements). That got all the attention.

The second was quieter. And honestly, more insidious.

Every DAO method in our codebase followed this pattern:

var db = _dbContextFactory.Create();
return query.ToListAsync().ContinueWith(t => {
    db.Dispose();
    return t.Result;
});

Looks safe, right? Factory creates. Continuation disposes. Ship it.

Except:
• The DbContext lives in a closure until GC collects it
• At 40 req/sec, contexts pile up by design
• Under load: 200+ DbConnectionPool instances in memory
• Connection pool exhaustion → 499 timeouts

The fix:

using (var db = _dbContextFactory.Create())
{
    return await query.ToListAsync();
}

Disposal goes from "eventually" to "51ms flat."

The misconception: "We're using a factory, so the factory manages the lifecycle."

No. The factory's job ends at .Create(). Disposal is always the caller's responsibility.

If it implements IDisposable, wrap it in using. Period.

Full deep dive: https://learnedgeek.com/Blog/Post/memory-leak-part-4-entity-framework-factory-disposal

