Pop quiz: Which Web API controller method leaks memory?

Method A:
```csharp
public async Task<HttpResponseMessage> GetData()
{
    var result = await _service.GetData();
    return Request.CreateResponse(HttpStatusCode.OK, result);
}
```

Method B:
```csharp
public async Task<IHttpActionResult> GetData()
{
    var result = await _service.GetData();
    return Ok(result);
}
```

Answer: Method A leaks. Badly.

We had 200+ controllers following this pattern. Every single one leaked HttpResponseMessage objects.

The problem: Web API's disposal contract differs by return type.

• Return IHttpActionResult → Web API disposes for you ✅
• Return HttpResponseMessage → You must dispose manually ⚠️

This isn't documented clearly. Microsoft's own examples show the leaking pattern.

Under load (100+ req/sec):
• Before fix: 2,257 HttpResponseMessage instances leaked
• After fix: < 100 instances

Production impact:
• 12 instances → 6 instances (50% cost reduction)
• Zero timeout errors
• Stable memory

The fix: Change return types to IHttpActionResult. Use Ok(), NotFound(), ResponseMessage().

Two years of pain. One return type change.

